n\n\n**Solutions**:\n1. **Option A (Add dynamic fields to pyproject.toml)**: Modify `pyproject.toml` to declare fields as `dynamic`:\n   ```toml\n   [build-system]\n   requires = ["setuptools", "wheel"]\n   version = "1.7.1"\n   \n   [project]\n   dynamic = ["version", "license", "authors", "classifiers", "dependencies", "optional-dependencies"]\n   ```\n2. **Option B (Convert setup.cfg to pyproject.toml)**: Move all configuration from `setup.cfg` to `pyproject.toml` in PEP 621 format.\n3. **Option C (Remove pyproject.toml entirely)**: Delete `pyproject.toml` to force setuptools to use only `setup.cfg`.\n4. **Option D (Add proper [project] table)**: Add complete PEP 621 configuration to `pyproject.toml`.\n\n**Recommended Approach**:\n**Option A (Add dynamic fields)** is recommended because:\n1. It\'s the minimal change that addresses the root cause\n2. It allows setuptools to read configuration from `setup.cfg` without PEP 621 validation errors\n3. It preserves both files and their intended purposes\n4. It\'s consistent with setuptools documentation for hybrid configurations\n5. It\'s less risky than removing `pyproject.toml` (which might break build system requirements)\n\n**Implementation Steps**:\n1. Modify `/root/fix_build_agent/process/project/g-py-crc32c/pyproject.toml` to add `[project]` table with `dynamic` field\n2. List all fields that are defined in `setup.cfg` as dynamic\n3. This tells setuptools: "These fields are defined elsewhere (in setup.cfg), don\'t validate them against PEP 621 schema"\n\n**Key Insight from Previous Attempts**:\n- Attempt 3 showed that simply emptying `pyproject.toml` wasn\'t enough - an empty file still triggers PEP 621 expectations\n- The real solution is to properly configure `pyproject.toml` to work with `setup.cfg`\n- Setuptools needs explicit permission to read fields from `setup.cfg` via the `dynamic` field\n- Strategy A (Config Repair) was exhausted after 3 attempts, but this is a new approach within Strategy A\n\n**Why This Should Work**:\nThe `dynamic` field in `pyproject.toml` tells setuptools which fields are defined outside of `pyproject.toml`. When setuptools sees `dynamic = ["license", ...]`, it knows to look for these fields in `setup.cfg` and won\'t try to validate them against PEP 621 schema.\n\n**Files to Examine**:\n1. `/root/fix_build_agent/process/project/g-py-crc32c/pyproject.toml` - Current: `[build-system]` only, needs `[project]` table with `dynamic` field\n2. `/root/fix_build_agent/process/project/g-py-crc32c/setup.cfg` - Complete configuration (correct after rollback, no `license_files`)\n3. `/root/fix_build_agent/process/project/g-py-crc32c/setup.py` - Build script that uses setup.cfg\n\n**Expected Outcome**:\nAfter adding `dynamic` fields to `pyproject.toml`, setuptools should:\n1. Stop complaining about fields being defined outside `pyproject.toml`\n2. Read configuration from `setup.cfg` without PEP 621 validation\n3. Accept `license = \'Apache 2.0\'` as a string (not dictionary)\n4. Build should proceed past the current error\n\n--- 【LESSONS FROM PREVIOUS ATTEMPTS】 ---\n- [Attempt 1] The Dockerfile patching introduced a syntax error: added \'-python\' suffix after the digest, which is invalid Docker image reference format. Docker digests must be at the end of the reference. The original error was a Python packaging configuration issue (pyproject.toml license field), but now we can\'t even start the build due to Docker syntax error.\n- [Attempt 2] Docker build succeeded after fixing syntax error. The C library compilation also succeeded. The error is now in Python packaging: setuptools expects license to be a dictionary with \'text\' key (per pyproject.toml schema) but reads \'Apache 2.0\' as a string from setup.cfg. Removing \'license_files\' resolved the file/text conflict, but now setuptools is trying to validate setup.cfg configuration against pyproject.toml schema. The minimal pyproject.toml with only [build-system] causes setuptools to expect PEP 621 compliance for all metadata. Need to either: 1) Add proper [project] table to pyproject.toml with license = {text = \'Apache-2.0\'}, 2) Add dynamic fields to pyproject.toml, or 3) Remove pyproject.toml entirely to force setuptools to use only setup.cfg.\n- [Attempt 3] Same error persists after emptying pyproject.toml. The warnings indicate setuptools still sees pyproject.toml with a [project] table and expects PEP 621 compliance. Emptying the file wasn\'t sufficient - an empty TOML file still exists, causing setuptools to expect configuration. The issue is deeper: setuptools behavior when pyproject.toml exists (even empty) triggers PEP 621 validation. Need to either: 1) Completely delete the file (not just empty it), 2) Add proper [project] table with dynamic fields, or 3) Ensure no [project] table exists in pyproject.toml. Strategy A exhausted after 3 attempts without progress.\n\n\n--- Configuration Files (Dockerfile, build.sh, etc.) ---\n\n### Content from: Dockerfile ###\n# Copyright 2022 Google LLC\n#\n# Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");\n# you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n# You may obtain a copy of the License at\n#\n#      http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n#\n# Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n# distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,\n# WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n# See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n# limitations under the License.\n#\n################################################################################\n\nFROM gcr.io/oss-fuzz-base/base-builder@sha256:5a22963e0582b5ce74e3dac5c175a321dc0cbe319c2851c370b885588327a055-python\nRUN git clone https://github.com/googleapis/python-crc32c\nCOPY build.sh *.py $SRC/\nWORKDIR python-crc32c\n\n### Content from: build.sh ###\n#!/bin/bash -eu\n# Copyright 2022 Google LLC\n#\n# Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");\n# you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n# You may obtain a copy of the License at\n#\n#      http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n#\n# Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n# distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,\n# WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n# See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n# limitations under the License.\n#\n################################################################################\n\ngit submodule update --init --recursive\n\nmkdir usr\nexport CRC32C_INSTALL_PREFIX=$(pwd)/usr\n\nmkdir google_crc32c/build\ncd google_crc32c/build\ncmake \\\n  -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \\\n  -DCRC32C_BUILD_TESTS=no \\\n  -DCRC32C_BUILD_BENCHMARKS=no \\\n  -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=yes \\\n  -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX:PATH=${CRC32C_INSTALL_PREFIX} \\\n  ../\nmake all install\ncd ../../\n\n\npython3 setup.py build_ext \\\n  --include-dirs=$(pwd)/usr/include \\\n  --library-dirs=$(pwd)/usr/lib \\\n  --rpath=$(pwd)/usr/lib\npip3 install -e .[testing]\n\n# Build fuzzers in $OUT.\nfor fuzzer in $(find $SRC -name \'fuzz_*.py\'); do\n  compile_python_fuzzer $fuzzer\ndone\n\n### Content from: fuzz_checksum.py ###\n#!/usr/bin/python3\n# Copyright 2022 Google LLC\n#\n# Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");\n# you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n# You may obtain a copy of the License at\n#\n#      http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n#\n# Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n# distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,\n# WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n# See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n# limitations under the License.\n\nimport atheris\nimport sys\n\nwith atheris.instrument_imports():\n  